##The virus hunters team sent new coronavirus-specific test kits to China this week for verification

Two new, more accurate coronaviruses will arrive in China this week.

At least 200 reagents will be sent to China for verification this week, Professor Lipkin, known as the "virus hunter, " said in an interview with Chinese Media Personality Yang Lan at Columbia University on February 24.

As of press time, contact with Lipkin for interface news was not returned. But Lu Jiahai, a professor at the public health at the National Sun Yat-sen University, confirmed the news to interface news.

According to media reports, Professor Lipkin's team amplified the PCR (polymerase chain reaction) with a special fluorescent stain, making the reagent several times more sensitive. In addition, the team used the world's unique serum chip to identify the most specific peptide for Elisa (Elisa) , which is accurate, cheap, effective and easy to operate. Both of these techniques help to improve the sensitivity and accuracy of diagnosis.

"[ the technical staff of Lipkin's team ] will arrive in two days. I am contacting them now and will bring them both ways, " Lu said.

It is important to test for antibodies to a variety of unknown pathogens, noted Lu, "We are working with high-resolution chip scanners that can read serum antibody chips, " he said. "It takes just a few days for the machine to be in place, and it will be possible to rapidly produce large amounts of the drug. "

Lipkin is director of the Center for infection and immunity at public health and an infectious disease specialist, also known as the "virus Hunter" in the International Journal of Epidemiology Field. Lipkin, the world's first scientist to use molecular methods to diagnose pathogens, was invited to fight SARS in China in 2003 and trained a large number of Chinese medical professionals to use the technology.

At the end of January 2020, Lipkin was invited by the Ministry of Health of the People's Republic of China to help assess the risks posed by COVID-19, to support new coronavirus detection and prevention and control research, and to meet with Zhong Nanshan, Zeng Guang and others of the National Health Council's High Level Panel of experts, lu Jiahai will accompany him all the way. So far, Lipkin has returned to the United States after a two-week self-imposed quarantine. His team is working with China to develop new coronavirus detection techniques, as well as better understanding of the virus's transmission and development path.

Recently, a number of experts in China have also pointed out that to identify the basis of the epidemic "inflection point" , the accuracy of the testing reagent is the key to find out the "bottom number" . Lipkin told the media, because the development of vaccines is time-consuming, so how to accurately diagnose and control the spread of the epidemic is still critical.

In response to the problem of "false negative" PCR nucleic acid tests for many of the new coronavirus isolated from infected people, Lu said that Lipkin's team is developing a multi-detection tool, to detect possible pathogens other than the new coronavirus.

"The existing test reagents rule out COVID-19, but they can't tell whether the infection is caused by COVID-19 or other common respiratory viruses, " Lu said.

Zhong Nanshan, an academician of the Chinese Academy of Engineering, said on February 23 during a teleconference with the Guangdong counterpart medical team in Jingzhou, Hubei Province, at the First Affiliated Hospital of the Guangzhou Medical University, it is imperative to distinguish between patients with new coronary pneumonia and those with influenza.

"The Lipkin team is working on an antibody test. It would not only be possible to identify the new coronavirus, but also to know whether the patient has other infections in the process of infection of the new crown, if it could introduce an antibody test,"Lu noted, that could be important in explaining whether patients have multiple or past infections, even in critically ill patients, even in their own settings.

"If the antibody test proves successful, we can also carry out a general survey of patients with mild illness, those with hidden infection, and even those who have recovered, then we can know how many people have been infected with the new coronavirus, " Lu said.

Lipkin also said that because the number of people infected with the new crown is not known, some people infected with the new crown but without any symptoms, antibody testing can detect these asymptomatic infections.

In China, reagents for differential diagnosis and antibody testing have been approved. On Feb. 22, the State Food and Drug Administration approved a test product from three companies in COVID-19, one of which was a reagent that identifies flu, new pneumonia and Parainfluenza, two more qualified antibody kits have also been approved.

"Both kits use colloidal gold, which can detect LGM antibodies in a patient's body, and can detect LGM antibodies on Day 7 of infection or day 3 of onset, which is very helpful for further diagnosis, " Zhong Nanshan said.
